# tl;dr

Define a class with appropriate data types.

    record CarSale ( String name , LocalDate whenSold ) {}

Then build a `List`, and call `List#sort`.

    new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(
        List.of(
            new Car( &quot;bmw&quot;, LocalDate.parse( &quot;2024-01-12&quot; ) ) ,
            new Car( &quot;jeep&quot;, LocalDate.parse( &quot;2023-02-12&quot; ) ) ,
            new Car( &quot;audi&quot;, LocalDate.parse( &quot;2023-12-12&quot; ) )
        )
    )
    .sort( CarSales :: whenSold )


# Details

If the main purpose of your class is to transparently communicate immutable data, define as a [record][1]. 

Represent date-time values using date-time classes. For a date-only value, use [`java.time.LocalDate`][2]. 

    record CarSale ( String name , LocalDate whenSold ) {}

The code calling upon this `CarSale` class should be parsing textual inputs as needed. (It is *not* the job of `CarSale` to clean up poorly formatted input text. See [*Separation of concerns*][3].)

    DateTimeFormatter f = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern( &quot;MM/dd/uu&quot; ) ;

    String input = &quot;01/12/24&quot; ;
    LocalDate ld = LocalDate.parse( input , f ) ;


Pass to the implicit constructor of our `CarSale` class. 

    CarSale cs = new CarSale( nameInput , ld ) ;

Collect those `CarSale` objects in a modifiable `List` such as a `ArrayList`.

    List&lt; CarSale &gt; carSales = new ArrayList &lt;&gt;() ;
    carSales.add( cs ) ;

Lastly, sort your list.  Pass a method reference to the getter method for the `LocalDate` object we populated. Objects of that class `LocalDate` know how to sort themselves. 

    carSales.sort( CarSales :: whenSold ) ;


Tip: Educate the publisher of your data about using only standard [ISO 8601][4] formats for data exchange of date-time values. 

    


